The paper deals with natural language processing and machine learning techniques applied to political discourse, which suggests it could belong to several sub-categories. cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely category, as it deals with natural language processing and understanding. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) are also likely categories, as the paper introduces an unsupervised methodology for extracting surface motifs and grouping them according to their latent rhetorical role. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) are less likely categories, but could still be relevant as the paper deals with social interactions and discourse analysis.
